# Documentation

Functional documentation lives in `docs/`. Keep it current when modifying features.

## Structure

- One file per feature/topic per language: `docs/{locale}/{feature}.md` (e.g. `docs/en/simulation.md`, `docs/nl/simulation.md`, `docs/fr/simulation.md`). Locales: `en`, `nl`, `fr`.
- Each doc **must** include YAML front matter with **roles** (target audience):

```yaml
---
roles:
  - technical   # for developers: implementation, APIs, config, code
  - admin       # for administrators: how to use/operate (non-technical)
  - user        # for end users: product usage (non-technical)
---
```

Use one or more roles per doc. Docs with role **admin** or **user** must stay non-technical (no code, file paths, or implementation details).

## Guidelines

- Write for the audience implied by the doc's roles.
- **Technical**: include purpose, usage, code examples; link to external docs for libraries.
- **Admin / user**: plain language; what the system does and how to use it; no code or APIs.
- Keep docs concise. Update them when changing related code.

## Admin zone entity docs

For every entity that has an admin zone page (`app/app/admin/{entity}/`):

- Create or update **`docs/{locale}/{entity}.md`** with role **admin** for each locale. Use the same terminology as in the app (see `messages/{locale}.json`, e.g. `admin.{entity}.title`, `admin.{entity}.columns.*`).
- Content: a **short purpose** (one or two sentences) and a **properties table**.
- The table lists each property (column/field shown in the admin) and a brief description. Omit UI-only columns (e.g. select, actions).
- When you add, rename, or remove columns or fields on an admin entity page, update the corresponding doc and its properties table so they stay in sync.

## When to Document

Document a feature when it:

- Has configuration or environment variables
- Integrates external services or libraries
- Has non-obvious behavior or conventions
- Has an admin zone page (see Admin zone entity docs above)
